{
  "text": "Along with protein, to achieve appropriate growth, the energy intake must match growth [CITATION_1] . Since fat is a major source of calories, accurate and precise measurement of fat is of equal importance to determining protein content. In our study, fat content ranged from 1.0 to 8.0 g/dL and impressively confirms that fat shows the highest variability of all macronutrients. Assuming a milk intake of 150 mL/kg/d and an enteral fat absorption of 85%, a variation of 7 g fat/dL translates to a variation of caloric intake of 75 kcal/kg/d. These figures illustrate why growth rates vary amongst infants even if protein intake is optimized (Fig. 2) .",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "41038646"
  },
  "bib_entries": {
    "41038646": {
      "title": "Aggressive nutrition of the very low birthweight infant",
      "abstract": "We propose an approach to nutrition of the VLBW infant that aims at minimizing the interruption of nutrient uptake engendered by premature birth. Our approach is aggressive in that it goes beyond current practice in several key aspects. The gap in nutrient intakes between the proposed aggressive approach and current practice will most likely disappear over the next few years as today's aggressive practice becomes tomorrow's standard practice. As the gap diminishes, so will the threat that nutritional deprivation poses to growth and development of VLBW infants."
    }
  }
}